<paragraph id="574036D4FFE2416FCA81EBE3FE6022CC" blockId="20.[151,1437,546,969]" box="[199,466,655,682]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE2416FCA81EBE3FEFA22CC" bold="true" box="[199,328,655,681]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Reference:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE2416FCB09EBFCFE6022CC" author="Hemp, C." box="[335,466,655,682]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" refId="ref16956" refString="Hemp, C. (2021) A Field Guide to the Bushcrickets, Wetas and Raspy Crickets of Tanzania and Kenya. Senckenberg Gesellschaft fur Naturforschung, Frankfurt, 451 pp." type="book" year="2021">Hemp 2021</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE2416FCA81EBDFFE192370" blockId="20.[151,1437,546,969]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE2416FCA81EBDFFED022A8" bold="true" box="[199,354,691,717]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE2416FCB9CEBDFFDAF22A8" box="[474,541,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE2416FC8A9EBDFFCF022A8" box="[751,834,691,717]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and spectrum of the song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE2416FCEC5EBDFFB7422AB" box="[1155,1222,691,718]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1287,1311]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,201,1247]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Power spectra of male calling songs in Hetrodini species" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392725/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE2416FCBF6EBBBFDA92294" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[432,539,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE2416FC905EBBBFC2A2297" box="[835,920,727,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,632,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-221@11.[151,1436,597,1753]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Acanthoplus, Gymnoproctus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes (figures of Acanthoplus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Acanthoplus discoidalis, B–C Acanthoplus longipes, D Gymnoproctus rammei, E Gymnoproctus sculpturatus, F Gymnoproctus spec., G Acanthoproctus cervinus, H Acanthoproctus diadematus, I Hetrodes pupus. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-mssection)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392729/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
) consists of long series of syllables (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE2416FCF2AEBB4FA2E2297" box="[1388,1436,728,754]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">type</typeStatus>
B in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE2416FCA88EB97FEA32373" box="[206,273,763,790]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE2416FCB0EEB97FE2C2370" box="[328,414,763,789]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE2416FCA81EA73FB312338" blockId="20.[151,1437,546,969]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE2416FCA81EA73FE8F235C" bold="true" box="[199,317,799,825]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Genitalia.</emphasis>
In structure, the titillator (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE2416FC82EEA73FD07235C" box="[616,693,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-41@13.[151,1436,237,1179]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Titillator and genitalic sclerites in Hetrodini, Enyaliopsina. First row A Cosmoderus femoralis (CH8627), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti (Kazimzumbwi), C Enyaliopsis carolinus (Minziro), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus (Rau Forest); second row E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 near ephippiatus (Mwala), F Enyaliopsis jennae (Uluguru), G Enyaliopsis spec. 2 (Mpwapwa), H Enyaliopsis spec. 3 (East Chenene); third row I Gymnoproctus rammei (Puge Simbo), J Gymnoproctus spec. (East Chenene)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392735/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Fig. 9I</figureCitation>
) is similar to some found in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE2416FCE28EA73FB43235C" authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1887" box="[1134,1265,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Enyaliopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE2416FCE28EA73FB43235C" box="[1134,1265,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Enyaliopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is relatively small, with broad basal parts, a stout middle section and an even slightly thicker short tip.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE2416FCA81EA0BFEA723AC" blockId="20.[151,1437,546,969]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
